Data Analysis with pandas¶

The United States Social Security Administration (SSA) has made available data on the frequency of baby names from 1880 through the present. Download data set US Baby Names 1880-2023 (names.zip, 7MB). Create a folder named data and unpack the contents of the .zip file there.

The ZIP file contains several text files (yob1880.txt, yob1881.txt, ...). Each file contains yearly data about the number of births for particular name. To safeguard privacy, the SSA restricted the list of names to those with at least 5 occurrences.

Each file contains multiple comma-separated values. Here are the first five rows of yob1880.txt:

Mary,F,7065
Anna,F,2604
Emma,F,2003
Elizabeth,F,1939
Minnie,F,1746

We will try to answer several questions such as:

  • How many boys/girls were born each year?
  • Which was the most popular boy/girl name each particular year?
  • ...

The DataFrame Data Structure

The main pandas data structure is the DataFrame, which you can think of as representing a table or spreadsheet of data.

We will first read the file "yob1880.txt" into a DataFrame. We will then obtain some basic information about the data.

In [5]:
# read one of the files and set header
names = pd.read_csv('data/yob1880.txt', names=['name', 'sex', 'births'])

Indexing and selecting data

There are three slicing methods for selecting row data: two explicit slicing methods, and a general case.

  1. Position-oriented (Python slicing style : exclusive of end)
  2. Label-oriented (Non-Python slicing style : inclusive of end)
  3. General (Either slicing style : depends on if the slice contains labels or positions
In [13]:
names.head()

Merge data

The data set is split into files by year, so let's merge this data in the following way:

  • assemble all of the data into a single DataFrame, and
  • add a year field.

We will use the concat command for this purpose:

In [59]:
# 2023 is the last available year right now.
years = range(1880,2024)

pieces = []
columns = ['names', 'sex', 'births']

for year in years:
    path = 'data/yob%d.txt' % year
    current = pd.read_csv(path, names=columns)
    
    current['year'] = year
    pieces.append(current)
In [60]:
# Concatenate everything into a single DataFrame.
# We have to pass ignore_index=True because we’re not interested in preserving the original row numbers.
df = pd.concat(pieces, ignore_index=True)
In [61]:
# rename the "names" column
df = df.rename(columns = {'names':'name'})

girls = df.loc[df.sex == 'F'].reset_index(drop=True)

Just for fun...¶

Let's see what pandas is capable to do in just one line of programming code...

Q14 What was the most popular name, based on the number of births, in the year 2023?

In [167]:
year = 2023
In [168]:
# Group the data by 'year' and find the most popular name
most_popular_names = df.loc[df.groupby('year')['births'].idxmax(), ['year', 'name']]
In [169]:
# Convert the result to a dictionary for easy lookup
most_popular_names_by_year = most_popular_names.set_index('year')['name'].to_dict()
In [170]:
# Retrieve the most popular name for a specific year
most_popular_names_by_year.get(year)
Out[170]:
'Liam'
In [171]:
# The most popular boy name in that year
df[df.sex == 'M'].loc[df.loc[df.sex == 'M'].groupby('year')['births'].idxmax(), ['year', 'name']].set_index(
    'year')['name'].to_dict().get(year)
Out[171]:
'Liam'
In [172]:
# The most popular girl name in that year
df[df.sex == 'F'].loc[df.loc[df.sex == 'F'].groupby('year')['births'].idxmax(), ['year', 'name']].set_index(
    'year')['name'].to_dict().get(year)
